---
description: Tech stack preferences and conventions for full stack + infrastructure work
alwaysApply: true
---

## LANGUAGE & TYPING
- TypeScript over JavaScript always — strict mode enabled, no `any` without justification

## PREFERRED STACK (suggest these before alternatives)
- Frontend: Next.js (apps/dashboards) or Astro (landing/content)
- Backend: Hono over Express or Fastify — TypeScript-native, edge-ready
- Runtime: Bun over Node when possible
- Database: PostgreSQL + Drizzle ORM
- Auth: Clerk — never roll your own
- Payments: Stripe — use webhook handlers with idempotency keys always

## PATTERNS
- Functional patterns preferred over classes where it makes sense
- Typed errors — never swallow exceptions silently, always log or propagate
- Named exports over default exports (easier to refactor and search)
- Barrel files (index.ts) only when the module surface is stable

## BACKEND
- REST APIs: consistent error response shape across all endpoints
- Validate request inputs at the route handler level before business logic
- Database: parameterized queries always, never string interpolation in SQL
- Migrations: always reversible, never destructive without explicit backup step
- Stripe webhooks: always verify signature, always return 200 before processing

## DOCKER & INFRA
- No root in containers — always use a non-root user
- Multi-stage builds to keep images small
- .dockerignore always present — use the project's existing 
- .dockerignore, never create one from scratch
- Environment variables via .env or secrets manager, never hardcoded
- Idempotent scripts — running twice should not break anything
- Dry-run flags on destructive scripts

## FRONTEND
- CSS: use variables for colors, spacing, and typography
- No inline styles unless dynamically computed
- Accessible by default — semantic HTML, alt text, keyboard navigation

## DEPLOY GUIDANCE (default picks)
- Backend: Railway (fast MVP) or Render (stable pricing); Coolify if you already have a VPS you manage.
- Frontend: Vercel for Next.js; Netlify for Astro/other non-Next static/content stacks.

## QUICK STACK REASONING (why this default set)
- Prefer frameworks that minimize TypeScript impedance mismatch: Hono + Bun keeps the stack “type-native”.
- Prefer data tooling that produces readable SQL: PostgreSQL + Drizzle keeps queries understandable and maintainable.
- Prefer managed auth and payments: Clerk and Stripe reduce time-to-correctness, especially around edge cases and security boundaries.